	doi = {10.2307/4313091},
	abstract = {New estimates of the total nutrient (N and P) load to the Baltic Sea are considerably higher than earlier calculations. Estimated total nitrogen loads is 1.2× 106 tons/year (53\% riverborne, 9\% direct municipal and industrial discharges, 11\% nitrogen fixation and 27\% atmospheric deposition), total phosphorus load 77{\textbackslash}times 10{\textasciicircum}3 tons/year (65\% riverborne, 28\% direct municipal and industrial discharges and 7\% atmospheric deposition). These figures may still be too low. The load may have increased about 4× for total nitrogen and about 8× for total phosphorus, due to man's activities. Available data indicate that phosphorus is deposited in large amounts in the sediment, and that nitrogen is lost from the sediment through denitrification.},
